1
00:02:15,301 --> 00:02:16,719
I want you to come quick.

2
00:02:17,928 --> 00:02:19,388
Don't go!

3
00:02:34,900 --> 00:02:39,237
Edward Lanman was sitting in
his pleasant house in London

4
00:02:40,280 --> 00:02:46,534
The sun was shining
It was an early morning in June, not quite...

5
00:02:58,503 --> 00:02:59,545
Iris.

6
00:03:00,128 --> 00:03:01,588
Iris, wait for me.

7
00:03:02,214 --> 00:03:04,216
Just keep tight hold of me and it'll be all right.

8
00:03:05,216 --> 00:03:07,468
-You won't keep still.
-I can't keep still.

9
00:03:08,302 --> 00:03:10,179
I can't catch up with you.

10
00:03:33,155 --> 00:03:36,784
-Iris, you've got bicycle oil on your ankle.
-I don't care, John.

11
00:03:39,619 --> 00:03:41,204
Those of you, our guests...

12
00:03:41,246 --> 00:03:42,872
... on whose magnificent generosity
we depend...

13
00:03:43,498 --> 00:03:45,624
...we really are most frightfully grateful...

14
00:03:46,709 --> 00:03:49,752
...will need no introduction to
one of our most distinguished graduates...

15
00:03:51,129 --> 00:03:54,424
... an honorary fellow, Dame Iris Murdoch.

16
00:03:55,591 --> 00:03:59,928
She's a noted philosopher as well as
author of some twenty-six novels.

17
00:04:00,595 --> 00:04:03,055
And we are honoured to have her with us today.

18
00:04:03,597 --> 00:04:07,224
As well as the distinguished
Warton Professor of Literature..

19
00:04:07,766 --> 00:04:10,060
...who has the great good fortune
of being married to her.

20
00:04:11,395 --> 00:04:13,063
I need say no more about her.

21
00:04:13,647 --> 00:04:14,732
For good wine needs no bush.

22
00:04:15,941 --> 00:04:18,277
But she will not mind comparison with...

23
00:04:19,403 --> 00:04:21,322
... say, a really fine vintage claret.

24
00:04:25,157 --> 00:04:28,742
... Dame Iris will speak to you
about the importance of education.

25
00:04:41,795 --> 00:04:46,132
Education doesn't make you happy.
And nor does freedom.

26
00:04:48,259 --> 00:04:52,262
We don't become happy
just because we're free -- if we are...

27
00:04:53,055 --> 00:04:55,098
... or because we've been educated, if we have.

28
00:04:56,223 --> 00:04:58,642
But because education may be the means...

29
00:04:59,559 --> 00:05:01,061
... by which we realise we are happy.

30
00:05:02,145 --> 00:05:03,479
It opens our eyes, our ears.

31
00:05:04,855 --> 00:05:06,690
Tells us where delights are lurking.

32
00:05:07,983 --> 00:05:10,611
Convinces us that there is only one freedom...

33
00:05:11,570 --> 00:05:13,070
... of any importance whatsoever.

34
00:05:14,029 --> 00:05:15,405
That of the mind.

35
00:05:16,323 --> 00:05:18,116
And gives us the assurance,the confidence...

36
00:05:19,326 --> 00:05:22,912
...to walk the path our mind,
our educated mind offers.

37
00:05:26,874 --> 00:05:30,459
I shall tell him all my love.

38
00:05:31,168 --> 00:05:34,129
All my soul's adoration.

39
00:05:35,756 --> 00:05:38,299
And I think he will hear me.

40
00:05:39,133 --> 00:05:42,303
And will not say me nay.

41
00:05:43,679 --> 00:05:47,139
It is this that gives my soul.

42
00:05:47,807 --> 00:05:52,144
All it's joyous elation.

43
00:05:52,895 --> 00:05:56,983
As I hear the sweet larks sing.

44
00:05:57,691 --> 00:06:03,319
In the clear air of the day.

45
00:06:03,944 --> 00:06:04,945
Yes, of course there's something fishy...

46
00:06:05,362 --> 00:06:06,530
... about describing people's feelings.

47
00:06:07,531 --> 00:06:08,907
Try hard to beaccurate, but...

48
00:06:09,616 --> 00:06:11,535
... as soon as you start to define
such and such a feeling...

49
00:06:11,576 --> 00:06:12,577
... language let's you down.

50
00:06:12,869 --> 00:06:14,871
When we really speak the truth,
words are insufficient.

51
00:06:15,372 --> 00:06:20,127
Almost everything,
except things like "pass the gravy" ...

52
00:06:20,584 --> 00:06:23,378
... is a lie of a sort.
And that being the case, I shall shut up.

53
00:06:26,005 --> 00:06:28,006
And pass the gravy.

54
00:06:33,136 --> 00:06:34,137
But love, or at least unsatisfied love...

55
00:06:34,721 --> 00:06:35,847
... is concerned as much with understanding.

56
00:06:36,472 --> 00:06:37,723
And real love, extreme love...

57
00:06:38,807 --> 00:06:40,225
... once it's recognised
has stamp of the indubitable...

58
00:06:40,809 --> 00:06:42,351
Ah, John, may I call you, John, may I?

59
00:06:42,768 --> 00:06:43,811
Meet Miss Murdoch.

60
00:06:44,228 --> 00:06:45,187
Iris, my dear, John Bayley.

61
00:06:45,521 --> 00:06:47,356
One of the more promising young lecturers
in the English School.

62
00:06:47,731 --> 00:06:51,359
Though I caught him out over
Old English grammar, his weaker side I fear.

63
00:06:51,776 --> 00:06:54,112
A minor question of Anglo-Saxon syntax.

64
00:06:57,822 --> 00:06:58,823
Wine!

65
00:07:00,408 --> 00:07:01,783
I mean...

66
00:07:02,200 --> 00:07:03,327
... It went down the wrong way.

67
00:07:04,244 --> 00:07:06,622
Yes, I like that.

68
00:07:07,414 --> 00:07:08,915
There is a right way down, of course.

69
00:07:09,458 --> 00:07:11,541
Amazing how most of us find it
without even thinking about it.

70
00:07:12,250 --> 00:07:13,501
I rarely think...

71
00:07:14,127 --> 00:07:15,253
If you think about it, you'll never find it.

72
00:07:16,212 --> 00:07:17,589
Best thing to do
is hang on and trust the body. I do.

73
00:07:19,424 --> 00:07:20,550
Human beings love each other.

74
00:07:21,842 --> 00:07:23,927
In sex, in friendship...

75
00:07:24,678 --> 00:07:26,220
... and when they're in love.

76
00:07:28,014 --> 00:07:29,848
And they cherish other beings.

77
00:07:30,599 --> 00:07:34,436
Humans, animals, plants - even stones.

78
00:07:35,895 --> 00:07:39,190
The quest for happiness
and the promotion of happiness--

79
00:07:40,191 --> 00:07:43,109
--is in all of this
and the power of our imagination.

80
00:07:45,402 --> 00:07:46,695
I'm writing a novel.

81
00:07:48,113 --> 00:07:51,241
I don't suppose you have the time
or the inclination to even read a novel.

82
00:07:52,034 --> 00:07:53,702
I've written one. It's going to be published.

83
00:07:54,536 --> 00:07:55,620
And I'm writing another.

84
00:07:56,287 --> 00:07:58,622
Can I read it?

85
00:07:59,456 --> 00:08:01,540
No-one has read It -- None of my friends.

86
00:08:03,458 --> 00:08:04,417
What's it about?

87
00:08:05,251 --> 00:08:07,671
About? It has something for everyone.

88
00:08:08,254 --> 00:08:09,923
A bit like Shakespeare?

89
00:08:09,965 --> 00:08:10,924
Perhaps, yes.

90
00:08:11,967 --> 00:08:14,177
Please don't talk to anyone about it.

91
00:08:14,803 --> 00:08:16,805
No. Course not.

92
00:08:16,888 --> 00:08:17,889
I won't tell a soul.

93
00:08:26,352 --> 00:08:29,397
Every human soul has seen,
perhaps even before their birth...

94
00:08:31,857 --> 00:08:36,319
... pure forms. Such as justice, temperance...

95
00:08:37,529 --> 00:08:38,613
... beauty ...

96
00:08:39,030 --> 00:08:41,365
... and all the great moral qualities
which we hold in honour.

97
00:08:42,825 --> 00:08:44,368
We are moved towards what is good...

98
00:08:45,160 --> 00:08:46,703
... by the faint memory of these forms.

99
00:08:48,371 --> 00:08:51,124
Simple - -and calm and blessed...

100
00:08:52,542 --> 00:08:55,126
...which we saw once in a pure clear light...

101
00:08:56,419 --> 00:08:57,628
... being pure ourselves.

102
00:09:03,925 --> 00:09:07,304
'Wholegrain'.
Do we have wholegrain or something other?

103
00:09:07,887 --> 00:09:10,680
What is whole?
Is It something in itself or does it have parts?

104
00:09:11,014 --> 00:09:12,015
Oh, spaghetti.

105
00:09:13,182 --> 00:09:14,267
If you have a whole you have a whole.

106
00:09:14,309 --> 00:09:15,310
Ooh, sausages.

107
00:09:16,185 --> 00:09:17,186
You and me is a whole.

108
00:09:17,562 --> 00:09:19,938
If you toddle off there's a hole in the whole.
Or, if I do.

109
00:09:20,689 --> 00:09:22,941
But a whole can't be broken,
it just forms another whole.

110
00:09:23,191 --> 00:09:24,151
-Baked beans.
-Baked beans.

111
00:09:25,151 --> 00:09:26,860
Do you want Premium points?

112
00:09:27,360 --> 00:09:28,403
Do we deserve them?

113
00:09:28,570 --> 00:09:29,571
-Do you want bags?
-Bags, yes.

114
00:09:30,447 --> 00:09:33,616
You know, it's all around us,
people like you and me talking nonsense.

115
00:09:33,782 --> 00:09:34,783
I know, I know.

116
00:09:35,409 --> 00:09:36,410
Bag for life:

117
00:09:37,453 --> 00:09:39,370
-For life?
-That's what it says.

118
00:09:39,787 --> 00:09:41,331
We have to ask, give you the choice.

119
00:09:42,123 --> 00:09:43,166
Ooh, rather.

120
00:09:44,166 --> 00:09:45,542
You just have to listen, that's the job.

121
00:09:46,001 --> 00:09:49,129
You call it a job but it's like music, what you do.

122
00:09:50,047 --> 00:09:53,550
You live with the angels,
speak their language, the music of the spheres.

123
00:09:54,967 --> 00:09:57,594
Nowadays the only language
anyone really understands...

124
00:09:58,011 --> 00:09:59,887
...is pictures. Paint the picture.

125
00:10:02,055 --> 00:10:04,057
See, now I'm bagged for life.

126
00:10:06,017 --> 00:10:07,852
Love's the only language everyone understands.

127
00:10:08,728 --> 00:10:09,771
Ooh love, yes.

128
00:10:10,146 --> 00:10:11,773
I can read It but I can't speak it.

129
00:10:20,612 --> 00:10:23,073
My coat's caught on your chair.

130
00:10:33,082 --> 00:10:36,084
And the captain said
as the two weevils dropped out of the biscuit...

131
00:10:36,542 --> 00:10:38,044
..."which would you rather have, Mr Smith?"

132
00:10:38,543 --> 00:10:39,544
"The bigger one, sir."

133
00:10:40,128 --> 00:10:43,382
"Wrong, Mr Smith, wrong."
"In the Navy you should always...

134
00:10:43,715 --> 00:10:44,715
...choose the lesser of the two weevils."

135
00:10:45,299 --> 00:10:46,300
Patrick O'Brian.

136
00:10:46,676 --> 00:10:48,928
"Between two evils
always choose the one you haven't tried before."

137
00:10:49,762 --> 00:10:51,471
Mea West. Oh my vest!

138
00:10:52,055 --> 00:10:53,430
I tore my vest again this morning.

139
00:10:53,681 --> 00:10:54,682
You must get some new vests.

140
00:10:55,140 --> 00:10:56,308
Jolly good.

141
00:10:57,393 --> 00:10:58,768
You must get some new vests.

142
00:10:59,936 --> 00:11:00,895
I just said that.

143
00:11:03,481 --> 00:11:05,817
You're always saying
that you just said something. Me too.

144
00:11:06,776 --> 00:11:08,943
Good job
you reminded me I had two lectures today.

145
00:11:09,569 --> 00:11:10,570
You remembered.

146
00:11:11,195 --> 00:11:14,115
No, but I remembered
to apologise for the one I forgot.

147
00:11:14,115 --> 00:11:15,116
They were very sweet about it.

148
00:11:16,117 --> 00:11:17,618
Glad not to have listen to you, I expect.

149
00:11:18,034 --> 00:11:19,035
Oh, I'm sure.

150
00:11:20,120 --> 00:11:21,538
They'd have been delighted
to have listened to you.

151
00:11:22,664 --> 00:11:23,831
I always have been.

152
00:11:34,631 --> 00:11:36,174
-Iris!
-John.

153
00:11:39,093 --> 00:11:41,095
Than kyou. Keep the change.

154
00:11:41,803 --> 00:11:44,097
-Janet. Janet!
-Oh my God, Iris.

155
00:11:45,557 --> 00:11:46,558
Am I late?

156
00:11:47,767 --> 00:11:50,520
Oh no, it's the hokie-cokie.
Everything will be over.

157
00:11:51,146 --> 00:11:55,773
Oh, John, wait. I've got my stocking caught up.

158
00:11:56,566 --> 00:11:58,858
Stupid things. Really.

159
00:12:11,329 --> 00:12:13,956
I'm not sure I'm entirely -- I'm so sorry.

160
00:12:15,749 --> 00:12:16,750
Oh, sorry.

161
00:12:19,918 --> 00:12:20,919
Cha-cha-cha.

162
00:12:28,175 --> 00:12:29,176
Cha-cha-cha.

163
00:12:33,179 --> 00:12:34,305
-Thank you.
-You too.

164
00:12:37,599 --> 00:12:38,934
That was my husband.

165
00:12:41,853 --> 00:12:42,811
Cha-cha-cha.

166
00:12:45,856 --> 00:12:47,358
Are you with Iris?

167
00:12:48,525 --> 00:12:49,651
Hoping so.

168
00:12:50,360 --> 00:12:51,777
You know we have...

169
00:12:51,818 --> 00:12:52,819
I thought we had.

170
00:12:52,861 --> 00:12:53,820
...nearly met.

171
00:12:54,238 --> 00:12:56,073
-Are you a friend of Iris?
-Yes.

172
00:12:56,781 --> 00:12:58,991
She seems to have a lot of f...

173
00:12:59,492 --> 00:13:06,330
Janet Stone. John Bayley.

174
00:13:06,956 --> 00:13:08,415
-How do you do?
-How do you do?

175
00:13:09,041 --> 00:13:10,501
Shall we?

176
00:13:10,668 --> 00:13:11,669
What are your rooms like?

177
00:13:12,211 --> 00:13:13,337
Adequate,thank you.

178
00:13:14,129 --> 00:13:15,673
I'd like to see them.

179
00:13:19,384 --> 00:13:21,718
Do you have a lot of friends?

180
00:13:22,094 --> 00:13:23,553
Is a list of my friends necessary?

181
00:13:23,970 --> 00:13:25,763
I justwondered if you had many.

182
00:13:26,389 --> 00:13:28,391
There aren't many people
that one wants to know one.

183
00:13:30,392 --> 00:13:32,394
Iris!

184
00:13:39,775 --> 00:13:40,775
You might fall.

185
00:13:41,859 --> 00:13:43,111
Would you like some champagne?

186
00:13:43,570 --> 00:13:44,529
That would be nice.

187
00:13:44,821 --> 00:13:47,574
I've had some since Christmas...
It does keep, doesn't it?

188
00:13:56,246 --> 00:13:58,622
I shouldn't be doing this.

189
00:13:59,081 --> 00:13:59,999
What?

190
00:14:00,416 --> 00:14:02,918
Having women in my room. It's not permitted.

191
00:14:03,752 --> 00:14:05,087
I wouldn't say you'd had me exactly.

192
00:14:06,297 --> 00:14:11,176
Have you danced before?

193
00:14:12,761 --> 00:14:13,929
It was all right, wasn't it?

194
00:14:15,096 --> 00:14:16,221
Oh, I think so.

195
00:14:16,680 --> 00:14:18,806
Broke the ice, so to speak.

196
00:14:19,098 --> 00:14:20,057
-"Ice"?
-What?

197
00:14:21,933 --> 00:14:23,643
It'll do.

198
00:14:24,603 --> 00:14:26,855
Aren't you particular
about words at your college?

199
00:14:27,397 --> 00:14:31,358
I'm only here under sufferance really,
as a tutor and guide.

200
00:14:32,109 --> 00:14:34,653
I get all the Americans
and Frenchmen to mother.

201
00:14:36,696 --> 00:14:38,156
You love words, don't you?

202
00:14:39,324 --> 00:14:40,742
If one doesn't have words, how does one think?

203
00:14:44,703 --> 00:14:46,121
Shall I do that?

204
00:14:47,289 --> 00:14:50,081
What is your novel about?

205
00:14:50,874 --> 00:14:52,334
About?

206
00:14:54,085 --> 00:14:55,085
How to be free.

207
00:14:55,753 --> 00:14:56,754
How to be good...

208
00:14:59,256 --> 00:15:00,424
...and how to love.

209
00:15:01,675 --> 00:15:03,385
Well, that's all there is, I'd say.

210
00:15:06,929 --> 00:15:09,514
Language is all very well, you know, but...

211
00:15:09,890 --> 00:15:12,059
...it's not the only way
of understanding each other.

212
00:15:13,602 --> 00:15:14,602
There's sight and...

213
00:15:14,977 --> 00:15:17,480
...and smell and...touch, of course.

214
00:15:22,691 --> 00:15:23,901
I love your nose.

215
00:15:26,111 --> 00:15:27,154
It's snub.

216
00:15:36,954 --> 00:15:37,955
Snubby...

217
00:15:38,496 --> 00:15:39,830
...snubby, snubby.

218
00:15:42,625 --> 00:15:44,210
it's snubby, snubby, snubby.

219
00:16:06,478 --> 00:16:07,479
Let me do that to you.

220
00:16:08,939 --> 00:16:09,940
Take off your jacket.

221
00:16:33,666 --> 00:16:36,711
If we were, as it were, married...

222
00:16:37,044 --> 00:16:38,337
...we could do this all the time.

223
00:16:39,046 --> 00:16:40,046
Perhaps?

224
00:16:41,798 --> 00:16:43,550
We should be doing it nearly all the time.

225
00:16:43,884 --> 00:16:45,427
Yes, but if...

226
00:16:51,264 --> 00:16:53,724
Thank you.

227
00:17:27,585 --> 00:17:28,586
Look.

228
00:17:38,844 --> 00:17:39,845
I'm stopping you working.

229
00:17:40,387 --> 00:17:41,639
Yes, well, I don't mind.

230
00:17:45,726 --> 00:17:47,186
How's it coming along?

231
00:17:48,353 --> 00:17:50,063
It's harder to write than all the others. Much.

232
00:17:50,812 --> 00:17:51,813
Have you noticed?

233
00:17:52,438 --> 00:17:56,817
Just that you've seemed...
puzzled every now and again.

234
00:17:57,567 --> 00:17:58,568
That's it, yes.

235
00:18:00,445 --> 00:18:01,571
Puzzled.

236
00:18:04,032 --> 00:18:09,329
Puzzled. It's a funny word.

237
00:18:10,622 --> 00:18:13,915
All words are like that
when you take them by surprise, aren't they?

238
00:18:15,958 --> 00:18:17,375
Have you got a title?

239
00:18:19,043 --> 00:18:20,378
'A lot of trees...

240
00:18:21,462 --> 00:18:22,672
...seem near.'

241
00:18:27,260 --> 00:18:28,260
We must stop it.

242
00:18:28,760 --> 00:18:29,761
What to do?

243
00:18:30,095 --> 00:18:33,722
The window, John, the window!
We must stop it.

244
00:18:34,723 --> 00:18:35,724
No. See...

245
00:18:36,600 --> 00:18:37,601
...it's gone.

246
00:18:46,358 --> 00:18:48,651
We all worry about going mad, don'twe?

247
00:18:51,487 --> 00:18:52,779
How would we know...

248
00:18:53,697 --> 00:18:55,574
...those of us who live in our minds anyway?

249
00:18:59,452 --> 00:19:00,912
Other people would tell us.

250
00:19:03,288 --> 00:19:04,289
Would they, John?

251
00:19:10,211 --> 00:19:12,171
I don't want to set the world...

252
00:19:12,754 --> 00:19:13,755
Sorry.

253
00:19:14,673 --> 00:19:19,593
...on fire.

254
00:19:20,051 --> 00:19:21,511
John Bayley.

255
00:19:39,651 --> 00:19:40,652
Haven't seen her for ages.

256
00:19:41,069 --> 00:19:42,946
Jolly good -- nice.

257
00:19:44,698 --> 00:19:46,616
Takes all sorts. Not that I ...

258
00:19:47,867 --> 00:19:50,076
...we're all men at St Anthony's.

259
00:19:50,951 --> 00:19:52,118
Do you like women?

260
00:19:52,452 --> 00:19:54,787
I mean, do women like you?

261
00:19:55,663 --> 00:19:56,831
